Recently, she proved that the peacock mantis shrimp has the fastest kick in the animal kingdom.", "whotheyare": "Biologist Sheila Patek is addicted to speed -- animal speed. She's measured the fastest animal movements in the world, made by snail-smashing mantis shrimp and the snapping mandibles of trap-jaw ants.", "whylisten": "

Sheila Patek, a UC Berkeley biologist, made a name for herself by measuring the hyperfast movements of snail-smashing mantis shrimp heels and bug-snapping ant jaws, using high-speed video cameras recording at up to 20,000 frames per second. In 2004, she and her team showed that peacock mantis shrimp had the fastest feeding strike in the animal kingdom, and that they are the only known animal to store energy in a hyperbolic paraboloid, a super-strong Pringles-shaped structure more often found in modern architecture.

Then in 2006, she and her team announced that trap-jaw ants had stolen the title of fastest striker from the mantis shrimp, when their research measured the ants' snapping jaws at an awesome 78 to 145 miles per hour, accelerating at 100,000 times the force of gravity. Patek's previous research focused on the sounds made by spiny lobsters, discovering that they used a mechanism similar to a violin. In 2004, she was named one of Popular Science magazine's "Brilliant 10." The Patek Lab at University of Massachusetts Amherst, where Patek is the principal investigator, continues to explore evolutionary questions through the integration of physiology, biomechanics, evolutionary analysis and animal behavior.

So, actually, I started working on what's called the Manta shrimp a few years ago because they make sound. This is a recording I made of a manta shrimp that's found off the coast of California. Uh, and while that's an absolutely fascinating sound, it actually turns out to be a very difficult project. And while I was struggling to figure out how and why mantis, shrimp or systematic pods make sound, I started to think about their appendages and manta shrimp are called manta shrimp after the praying mantises, which also have a fast feeding appendage. And I started to think, Well, maybe it'll be interesting while listening to their sounds to figure out how these animals generate very fast feeding strikes and said today I'll talk about the extremes to Mata pod strike work that I've done in collaboration with white Corfu and Roy Caldwell. So magistrate, come in two varieties. There are spears and smashes, and this is a spearing mantis shrimp or systematic pod, and he lives in the sand and he catches things that go by overhead. So a quick, a quick strike like that on if we slow it down a little bit. This is the mantis shrimp. The same species recorded 1000 frames per second, played back at 15 frames for second.
